    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-12-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-12-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="195"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d195">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">123 Hurley, Gen. Pat.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Secretary of State</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-27">December 27,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum for the President</hi>
                </p>
                <p>Senator Tom Connally told me during the hearings<note n="45" xml:id="d195fn45"
                        >Probably Congressional hearings preceding the enactment of the Department
                        of State Appropriation Act, 1946 (Public Law 61, 79th Cong., 1st sess., May
                        21, 1945; 59 Stat. 169).</note> that he felt Pat should get out of uniform
                    now that he is an Ambassador.</p>
                <pb facs="0227" n="213" xml:id="pg_213"/>
                <p>That is in conformity with our general practice and I have told him<note n="46"
                        xml:id="d195fn46">Telegram No. 1693, December 21, 9 p.m., not
                        printed.</note> that statutory requirements<note n="47" xml:id="d195fn47"
                        >Public Law 305, 78th Cong., 2d sess., June 28, 1944 (double-pay
                        restriction); 58 Stat. 395.</note> made it necessary for him to be
                    transferred from the Army to our State Department rolls as of the date of his
                    appointment. I also told him that as soon as convenient, he should put on
                    civilian clothes. I trust this will meet with your approval.<note n="48"
                        xml:id="d195fn48">Marginal notation by President Roosevelt: “ERS Jr. OK
                        FDR”.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>E. R. <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius, Jr.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
